{"key":"post-13167271","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>13167271</id>\n<content>You don't need to dissolve the gypsum.&amp;nbsp; Simply mix it in with the substrate.&amp;nbsp; The mycelium will get what it needs.&amp;nbsp; After all, mycelium can munch down vermiculite, so gypsum is no problem either.&amp;nbsp; I mix the gypsum in with dry substrate ingredients, and then add moisture to the proper level.&amp;nbsp; There also is no 'recipe'.&amp;nbsp; Simply mix what you have in whatever quantities you have them.&amp;nbsp; A mixed substrate is superior to a single-ingredient substrate, thus if you mix horse or cow manure, coir, vermiculite, straw, etc., the results will be superior to any one by itself.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>13167293</next>\n<prev>13167262</prev>\n<first>13164584</first>\n<last>13169087</last>\n<when>1283995623</when>\n<utime>09/09/10 04:27 AM</utime>\n</post>"}